: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Fire chemistry &am=
p; severity</span></u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br><span style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(33, 33, 33);">FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers stored i=
n the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escalation to a=
 second alarm; ASURNZ also records cavity smoke migration and roof-edge heat=
 (deformed soffit, melted gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. T=
aken together, these factors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic r=
esidues and deep smoke penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly=
, and HVAC, so a visual-only approach is not appropriate.</span></span><o:p>=
</o:p></div></div></div></div></div><div><div><div><div><div style=3D"margin=
: 0cm; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font=
-size: 10pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">As such, could you please provide a wr=
itten, insurer-funded plan and schedule setting out methods/standards, pass c=
riteria, dates, and named leads. The detailed methodology and acceptance thr=
esholds are to be designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts=
 (hygienist, CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector,=
 certifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a moisture/=
corrosion specialist) and laboratories. &nbsp;Also it is my understanding th=
at AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reinstatement practice note) expects intrus=
ive investigation and formal sign-offs where the primary structure or extern=
al moisture/fire systems are affected, including removal of wet linings/insu=
lation, a CPEng report on the impact to the primary structure, LBP design/su=
pervision where applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><o:p></o:p>=
</div></div></div></div></div><div><div><div><div><div style=3D"margin: 0cm;=
 font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size:=
 10pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">I also believe that at a minimum&nbsp;the pl=
an should address intrusive verification of roof/eaves (including underlay, b=
attens, fixings, and truss nail-plates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity c=
hecks where odour is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor south/we=
st elevations and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hygienist c=
learance before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance for heat-p=
ump heads and the roof-space gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation electr=
ical verification to AS/NZS 3000 with certification; plumbing system integri=
ty testing and disinfection where indicated; moisture logging and corrosion/=
pH-chloride screening of representative framing/fasteners and masonry; and i=
ndependent IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and re-occupation.</span>=
<o:p></o:p></div></div></div></div></div><div><div><div><div><div style=3D"m=
argin: 0cm; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=
=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Scope adequacy</span></u><span style=3D"font-size: 10p=
t;"><br>=46rom the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into first-flo=
or cavities with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge=
 heat with deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope a=
ppears focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal, selective electrical ch=
ecks, =E2=80=9Ctest &amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas) rather than the real da=
mage pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, corrosion).<br>Respectfull=
y, it is not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromised. Non-cha=
rred structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar exposed to s=
moke and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutralised or repl=
aced.</span><o:p></o:p></div></div></div></div></div><div><div><div><div><di=
